A Czech Discovery: An Effective Substance Even in the 'Clattered' HIV Viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds capable of tempering the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of this improved substance is that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, as some medicines are already accessible.
The AIDS disease cannot be cured until now.
However, the life of patients can be significantly prolonged by a mixture of medicines that prevent replication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the replication of the virus is not completely suppressed, the so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, the drugs no longer work.
The work of experts from three Institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠCHT Prague and Heidelberg University shows the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They showed that the substances called metalocarborans have an effect on albumin, responsible for the spread of HIV.
Metalocarborans are made up of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus differently from all medicines used today, and that is why they can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work scientists find new, ‘improved’ compounds, prepared knowing the molecular mechanism of their link to the virus albumin.
The metalocarborans have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyhedral cages composed of the atoms of boron, hydrogen and carbon are united by the atom of metal, in this case by cobalt.
