The pneumococcal vaccine will be free and voluntary
The pneumococcal vaccine from January will put an end to the usual customs.
As a first vaccine it must be free for families and at the same time voluntary.
However, there are already opinions that the mandatory vaccine would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of the free anti-neumococcal vaccine are culminating.
The Institute of Medicinal Products is already setting the maximum prices for vaccines, which will be covered by insurance companies.
Experts have already made this clear in the vaccination procedure.
The new vaccine
Free vaccines for children born in August
From January, children born since 2 August last year can receive the pneumococcal vaccine free of charge.
The condition is that you have not received a dose of the vaccine before.
Those who started with the vaccine last year or before have to cover other doses of the vaccine as well.
The first dose of the vaccine must be received between the third and fifth month of child age.
Last year, a fourth of the families volunteered to vaccinate their children against pneumococci.
However, parents paid for a dose of 1600 krona and more.
Four doses are needed to vaccinate younger children.
Experts generally estimate that insurance companies will spend on vaccines from 300 to 450 thousand krona annually.
Without clutches they will save in treatment, which is needed for children not vaccinated.
So far the state has spent throughout the vaccination of children approximately 500,000 annually.
The covered vaccination was initiated by the so-called Janota package.
Pneumococcus is the cause of media otitis, but also of severe infections including meningitis and septicemia.
According to research in hospitals, 28 children not older than 10 years of age die from pneumococcal infections in our country each year.
In addition to the Czech Republic, the coverage of the neomococcal vaccine in children was introduced in approximately 40 countries.
Will the vaccine be mandatory?
At the same time, however, there are opinions that this vaccine could be mandatory in the future.
From January it must be covered by insurance and voluntary companies.
The mandatory vaccine would be better, for example noted Rudolf Kalovský, the head of the Nahlas civic association.
Its association has been spreading pneumococcal vaccines for a long time.
The experts at an international conference, in which our association participated, were not fully satisfied with the fact that we have the voluntary vaccine.
It's not completely ideal.
On the other hand, we are happy to achieve at least this.
I think this is the path that we now have to take, mentioned Kalovský.
The Ministry of Health, however, does not want to change the vaccination procedure against pneumococci.
At this point we do not think at all, said his spokesman Vlastimil Sršeň.
The voluntary vaccine has its disadvantages, doctors say
The president of the pediatrician society Odborná společnost praktických dětských lekařů Hana Cabrnochová acknowledges that the voluntary vaccine has its disadvantages.
If all the children were to receive the vaccine, they could be reasoned on the reduction in the number of doses. "In the situation, when the vaccine costs such a high amount, we relatively understand the political decision to have initiated the vaccination as voluntary," Cabrnochová says.
Experts expect that from the coming year over 80 percent of young parents will allow their babies to vaccinate against pneumococci.
The pneumococcal vaccine is a big change also because as the first vaccination in children is covered by health companies, not by the state.
Insurance companies should spend more money on prophylaxis, to save later on in treatment, explains Cabrnochová.
The doctors will have to buy the vaccines for themselves.
However, pediatricians are concerned about the purchase of vaccines.
Previously, vaccines had to be purchased by insurance companies and distributed to doctors, as when the state gives them other vaccines.
Some Members, however, were afraid, that insurance companies could "get the money out of health insurance."
That's why doctors will have to buy the vaccines and wait until they're paid by insurance companies.
It is estimated that pediatricians will invest in vaccines 40,000 per month, which is a remarkable sum.
It won't be easy, says Cabrnochová.
