A UN group outlines a plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference, which has so far been characterized by challenging positions and mutual recriminations, attracted renewed attention on Friday with the release of a document that foresees ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations carrying most of the burden on their shoulders in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that is running out of time, with over 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
Developed by an ad hoc UN working group, the text does not talk about how much money rich countries would give to the poor to cope with global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a variety of options for key questions, which include how developed economies and major emerging economies would cut their coal production, and what would be the limit of the overall increase in the temperature that political strategists would be willing to tolerate.
This gives a lot of flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, senior representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote the six-page paper, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what UN top climate official Yvo de Boer described as "the great panorama."
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 2020 by 25 to 45 per cent, compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries would reduce their emissions during the same period between 15 and 30 per cent.
Together, countries would cut emissions between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also encouraged the talks on Friday, promising to provide $3.600 million annually over the next three years, to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
However, on Friday the same kind of verbal fireworks that have dominated the talks last week were presented.
The United States special climate envoy Todd Stern rejected the claims that require mandatory greenhouse gas emission cuts for industrialized countries, compared with volunteers from major emerging economies, if not funded by the developed world.
The maneuver indicated that the Obama administration is taking a tougher line with China, with respect to what Bush administration officials did just two years ago.
The United States will not agree without major developing countries moving forward and taking action, said Stern, who also regretted that the text did not do enough to ensure that cuts could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his remarks an hour after the Deputy Minister for Foreign Affairs of China He Yafei said that the U.S. maximum climate negotiator lacked "common sense", or was "very irresponsible" for saying earlier in the week that the United States would not economically help China cope with global warming.
With the future economic path of the major powers of the world at stake, the lines of failure have erupted both within the developing world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is both to save individual economies and to save the planet, with China and the United States facing their respective obligations, while the poorest nations insist that the twenty-four most influential countries in the world are ignoring the scientific imperative to take the most courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it is not surprising that the main powers are discussing who should cost the costs to limit greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries have become more aggressive trying to contain large issuers responsible for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic hegemony is being developed, supported Ulate, who also works as a regional adviser on climate change in Mexico and Central America, for International Conservation.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the main participants say that the talks will result in a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, with 43 members, prepared a preliminary treaty proposal of 24 pages early in the morning of Friday.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said that the push of small island nations has "made political pressure on the entire political process," partly because they are now unified and demand the action of emerging economies, such as China and India.
The talks took on a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that most exceptional issues must be resolved before the heads of government come to a close.
High-level officials, such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Deputy Minister, descended from the planes and rushed to the Belle Center corridors, to closed-door meetings and press conferences, in order to be able to delineate claims that will be decided next week.
The absolute disorder of the meeting (from every day 13,000 people enter and leave the convention center, activists playing the guitar show night shows mocking the countries they believe are selling, and preliminary hand-to-hand proposals are passed instead of by mail), poses a challenge.
The intensity only builds: almost all key ministers are here right now, and on Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the major leagues, said Carlos Manuel Rodríguez, vice president for the global policy of International Conservation.
Heavy weights are coming.
