Management revolution or end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies with regard to their employees recalls the position of companies with regard to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a matter for employees to adhere to "values" identified from above as previously intended to impose on consumers products thought of by factory technicians.
By putting the customer in the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave way to market conquer strategies... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are unrelated to customers' preference factors is repeated regularly.
Demobilisation of employees can end up in a deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that affects particularly executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R & D and, even more, business intelligence.
In fact, the BI (Business Intelligence) "requires that all parties involved (...) have proactive behaviour and prospective vision"; it requires a commitment on the part of employees that is completely opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian direction.
For this reason, we call for a managerial revolution, which would be to put employees at the centre of the company's concerns as well as the customer.
Internal opinion polls have a relative usefulness
Do internal opinion polls, such as the Orange questionnaire among its employees, encourage management revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I could verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many rounds, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did! B989
- Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great engineering schools, they interpret psychology in a mechanical way.
They adopt, for intellectual convenience, the old conductive theory that the American "neurosciences" have recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media have spread widely behind them.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the "commands" (sic) of the commitment of the executives, a recent Ipsos research published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms the managers in a mechanical management position, which is not adapted to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies, implies adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists of integrating into any reasoning or business management practice, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means to make reality part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only studies from the Motifuntional Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
The studies showed that they judge their company on the basis of a default dox that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of the mobilisation factors, business managers can control, predict and anticipate their "social development" and relocate the management of human resources "in place".
In this way, they create a favourable ground for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
