The cradle of the dinosaur
The Tawa Hallae had the same appearance as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: a two-metre-long and 1.50-meter-high animal that ran over the two strong hind legs, had an enlarged head with sharp teeth and curves, short arms with hoop-shaped claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple million years later, it would not have been something special.
But the Tawa Hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of Texas University in Austin and colleagues in the Science magazine on Thursday.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at that time was in a dry area of the Pangea Supercontinent in the equator.
Tawa opened a new window towards the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relations, the propagation and the characteristics of the first dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation in Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico in 2006.
Sometimes we have found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, this is something unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis member of Utah's Natural History Museum team.
Researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation, the remains of five specimens were gathered in total.
A finding confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Many Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt is an exceptional finding: "The dinosaur fossils of the Triassic are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not share such enthusiasm at all.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, for example Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current opinion, dinosaurs appeared for the first time about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these first dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Therefore, the experts discuss, for example, when the sauris were divided into their three most important genealogical lineages: the carnivorous teropods among which are the Tyrannosaurus Rex, Velociraptor and also the birds, the quadruped sarropods known as "long neck" and their relatives, and the Herbivoric Ornithischia (sauriums with oat pelvis), to those belonging, for example, to the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to Nesbitt's analysis and his colleagues, Tawa Hallae is a primitive teropod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
For example, in the skull of Tawa, researchers found signs of airbags, such as those that also own the descendants of the teropopods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In the case of Tawa foundlae also the bones of the spine were evidently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the teropod with the oldest and most primitive air bags, comments Randall Irmis.
Because the related line of the later giant sarropods also had air bags and light bones, it was likely that the common predecessors of both groups would already produce this useful innovation.
At least three migratory waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs so far known lived in South America, researchers deduced that the sauris arose there for the first time.
Therefore, the three genealogical lineages separated at first and spread from South America across all corners of the Earth, which by then still formed a unique earthly mass, the Supercontinent Pangea.
However, the facts say that the team found the remains of two other teropods together with Tawa not very closely related.
All three cannot descend from a single parented predecessor, the researchers argue.
We believe that at least three migratory waves were given to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science Study.
Of course, there are also opponents.
An even older species, Silesaurus, who belongs to a group of dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, comments the paleontologist of Bonn Martin Sander.
His opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many fossils of dinosaurs are still being preserved, while in other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how the dinosaurs evolved from a relatively rare collateral line of reptiles to the dominant terrestrial vertebrates of the Mesozoic remains an enigma.
Meanwhile, in the Triassic the dinosaurs still shared their vital space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of the current crocodiles and the pterosaurians and with many other savours.
Toward the end of the Triassic the dinosaurs expanded worldwide and many new species developed, while the kinship extinguished at the limit of the Triassic towards the Jurassic.
Successful Stories Were Not Eternal
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
A massive extinction may have been given to which dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles may not.
Or dinosaurs were better adapted, so they could defeat the opponents in the area.
Successful stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact halts the rise of a group of species, which had also evolved in the Triassic and since then had a miserable existence: mammals.
